## Architecture Overview

### Hexagonal Architecture

The application is organized in concentric layers. Dependencies always point **inward**:

```
Presentation (HTTP)
    ↓
Application (Use Cases)
    ↓
Domain (Business Logic)      ← No dependencies on outer layers
    ↑
Infrastructure (DB, APIs)    ← Implements domain interfaces
```

**Project structure for NestJS:**
```
src/
├── domain/                  # Pure business logic — zero framework dependencies
│   ├── entities/            # Domain entities with business behavior
│   ├── value-objects/       # Immutable typed values (Email, Money, etc.)
│   ├── events/              # Domain events
│   └── repositories/        # Repository interfaces (ports) — NOT implementations
├── application/             # Orchestration layer
│   ├── use-cases/           # One file per use case
│   ├── services/            # Application services
│   └── dtos/                # Input/Output DTOs
├── infrastructure/          # External world adapters
│   ├── database/            # Repository implementations (Mongoose/Prisma)
│   │   ├── schemas/         # Mongoose schemas or Prisma models
│   │   └── repositories/    # Concrete repository classes
│   ├── http/                # NestJS controllers and modules
│   └── services/            # External API adapters
└── shared/                  # Cross-cutting concerns
    ├── config/              # Configuration (never process.env directly in domain)
    ├── exceptions/          # Shared exception types
    └── utils/               # Pure utility functions
```

**Project structure for legacy Node.js (maintain existing patterns):**
```
src/
├── presentation/            # Controllers and routes
├── application/             # Services and validators
├── domain/                  # Domain models and repository interfaces
└── infrastructure/          # DB access and external services
```

